[
    {
        "content": "<p>I just wanted to record some findings from my recent search for a form of undirected graph composition in the <a href=\"#narrow/channel/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Baas.27s.20hyperstructures/with/595769484\">hyperstructures thread</a>. I was complicating this theme by simultaneously looking for a hierarchical structure (networks of networks). Better to treat them separately. (Yet a further theme concerned which Segal conditions to apply, which again can be put to one side.)</p>\n<p>I suspect that there's something of use to ACT systems theory in all of this.</p>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/algebraic+pattern\">[[Algebraic patterns]]</a> provide an excellent framework for different modes of composition: categories, operads, properads, ...</li>\n<li>A key aspect of an algebraic pattern is the factorization of any morphism into an inert and an active morphism. </li>\n<li>Inerts play a bookkeeping role, tracking variables, whereas actives capture composition. (To see them at work for the simplicial pattern on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Delta</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span></span></span></span>, i.e., the composition of categories, you can watch <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"751249\">@David Jaz Myers</span> in a <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=52AsVTxHXU0\">Topos Berkeley seminar</a> and also a <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3VP3ZfgfpTg\">2-torial</a>.) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ω</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Omega</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Ω</span></span></span></span>, the dendroidal category, provides the pattern for operads.<div class=\"youtube-video message_inline_image\"><a data-id=\"52AsVTxHXU0\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=52AsVTxHXU0\"><img src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/36975400211ae175d5d62fdbbc65c95a34190dce/68747470733a2f2f692e7974696d672e636f6d2f76692f35324173565478485855302f6d7164656661756c742e6a7067\"></a></div><div class=\"youtube-video message_inline_image\"><a data-id=\"3VP3ZfgfpTg\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3VP3ZfgfpTg\"><img src=\"https://uploads.zulipusercontent.net/bd1d260bc8af16c035fa55e59ec97fea29be755a/68747470733a2f2f692e7974696d672e636f6d2f76692f335650335a6667667054672f6d7164656661756c742e6a7067\"></a></div></li>\n<li>There are algebraic patterns for undirected and directed <em>connected</em> graphs. These are the <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>U</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.109em;\">U</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi>U</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">/</mi><mi mathvariant=\"fraktur\">o</mi></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">U_{/\\mathfrak{o}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0385em;vertical-align:-0.3552em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.109em;\">U</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3448em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.5198em;margin-left:-0.109em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">/</span><span class=\"mord mathfrak mtight\">o</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3552em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> of Philip Hackney's <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2109.06231\">Categories of graphs for operadic structure</a>. These provide patterns for modular operads and wheeled properads.</li>\n<li>Elsewhere, (Question 5.9 of <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2208.13852\">Segal conditions for generalized operads</a>), Philip asks for nonconnected versions of these to be able to approach (wheeled) PROPs, non-connected modular operads, etc.</li>\n<li>The <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ξ</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">×</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Xi^{\\times}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ξ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">×</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> of Sophie Raynor's <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.20262\">Modular operads, iterated distributive laws and a nerve theorem for circuit algebras, Theorem 8.4</a> looks like it answers some of what's wanted in the undirected case, giving rise to an algebraic pattern on which Segal presheaves are circuit algebras. The category of circuit algebras is equivalent to the Eilenberg-Moore category of algebras for a monad on Joyal and Kock’s graphical species category.</li>\n<li>Morphisms in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ξ</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">×</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Xi^{\\times}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ξ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">×</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> possess <em>ternary</em> factorization: composition (graphs of graphs); deletion; and étale maps. These allow for relevant network operations : refinements of nodes into graphs; forgetting substructure; locating subgraphs. An ordinary factorization arise from counting the first as the actives and the second and third together as inerts. There is then an algebraic pattern structure on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ξ</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">×</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Xi^{\\times}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ξ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">×</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</li>\n<li>Constructing a <em>directed</em> version of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ξ</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">×</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Xi^{\\times}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ξ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">×</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> would relate the apparatus of algebraic patterns to Joachim Kock's whole-grain approach to Petri nets.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>That's about as far as I've reached in that direction. There's surely some potential here to bring parts of categorical systems theory into relation with interesting topics in mathematics and mathematical physics. As for the hierarchical structure that Nils Baas sought, there's a wreath (<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>≀</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\wr</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">≀</span></span></span></span>) composition available for algebraic patterns.</p>",
        "id": 596458345,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1779284917
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I should read more closely. The directed version is already there. </p>\n<ol start=\"9\">\n<li>There is a directed or <em>oriented</em> version of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">GS</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">GS</span></span></span></span>, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ξ</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">×</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Xi^{\\times}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ξ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">×</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, etc. in <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.20262\">Modular operads, iterated distributive laws and a nerve theorem for circuit algebras</a> derived by working in the slice over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Di</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">D</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span></span></span></span>, where this <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>D</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">Di</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">D</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">i</span></span></span></span> provides the orientations. So there are <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>O</mi><mi>G</mi><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">OGS</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">O</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">GS</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>O</mi><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Ξ</mi><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">×</mo></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">O\\Xi^{\\times}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">O</span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\">Ξ</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7713em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">×</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>, etc. Segal presheaves on the latter are wheeled props (Corollary 8.6).</li>\n</ol>",
        "id": 596676313,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1779354659
    },
    {
        "content": "<ol start=\"10\">\n<li>The monad <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{O}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8556em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">O</span></span></span></span> on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">GS</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.0576em;\">GS</span></span></span></span>, the category of graphical species, is such that its EM-algebras are circuit algebras.  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">O</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{O}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8556em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">O</span></span></span></span> factorizes into three monads, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">O</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">D</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{O}=\\mathbb{L}\\mathbb{D}\\mathbb{T}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8556em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">O</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">LDT</span></span></span></span>.  In the oriented version, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">O</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{O}^{or}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8556em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">O</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">or</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> on oriented graphical/digraphical species, the EM-algebras are oriented circuit algebras (equivalently, wheeled props).  <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">O</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{O}^{or}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8556em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">O</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">or</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> factorizes as <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">L</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">D</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">T</mi><mrow><mi>o</mi><mi>r</mi></mrow></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{L}^{or}\\mathbb{D}^{or}\\mathbb{T}^{or}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">L</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">or</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">D</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">or</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">T</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\" style=\"margin-right:0.0278em;\">or</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. A Petri net, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>P</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">P</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.1389em;\">P</span></span></span></span>, is a <em>flat</em> digraphical species. The application of the monads successively adds: all sequential firings, units (null firings), concurrent firings.</li>\n</ol>",
        "id": 596730093,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1779368356
    },
    {
        "content": "<ol start=\"11\">\n<li>As for what this technology could bring to systems theory, one suggestion from Raynor, \"Given a circuit algebra <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>, the bar construction for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">O</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">L</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">D</mi><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">T</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{O}=\\mathbb{L}\\mathbb{D}\\mathbb{T}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8556em;vertical-align:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">O</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">LDT</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> may be viewed as a rulebook for <em>zooming in and out</em> of networks decorated by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span>\" (p. 3). Presumably this carries over to the oriented case.</li>\n</ol>",
        "id": 596770825,
        "sender_full_name": "David Corfield",
        "timestamp": 1779376810
    }
